on, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1312–1345":"1312–1345","1300–Male":"1300–Overleden","1326–1379":"1326–1379","1342–1374":"1342–1374","1273–Male":"1273–Overleden","1280–1312":"1280–1312","1326":"1326","1379":"1379","1312":"1312","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","Aft. 1312":"na 1312","1342":"1342","1374":"1374","1273":"1273","1280":"1280","Honiton, Devonshire, England":"Honiton, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Enland, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1312–1345":"1312–1345","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1326–1379":"1326–1379","1342–1374":"1342–1374","1273–Male":"1273–Deceased","1280–1312":"1280–1312","1326":"1326","1379":"1379","1312":"1312","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","Aft. 1312":"after 1312","1342":"1342","1374":"1374","1273":"1273","1280":"1280","Honiton, Devonshire, England":"Honiton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Enland, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Tremenent was born in 1312, in Honiton, Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard Tremenent, was 39 and his mother, Isabel De Clist, was 32. He had at least 1 daughter with Margaret Donnett. He died in 1345, in his hometown, at the age of 33."},"et":{"1312–1345":"1312–1345","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1326–1379":"1326–1379","1342–1374":"1342–1374","1273–Male":"1273–Surnud","1280–1312":"1280–1312","1326":"1326","1379":"1379","1312":"1312","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","Aft. 1312":"pärast 1312","1342":"1342","1374":"1374","1273":"1273","1280":"1280","Honiton, Devonshire, England":"Honiton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Enland, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1312–1345":"1312–1345","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1326–1379":"1326–1379","1342–1374":"1342–1374","1273–Male":"1273–Kuollut","1280–1312":"1280–1312","1326":"1326","1379":"1379","1312":"1312","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","Aft. 1312":"1312 jälkeen","1342":"1342","1374":"1374","1273":"1273","1280":"1280","Honiton, Devonshire, England":"Honiton, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Enland, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1312–1345":"1312–1345","1300–Male":"1300–Décédé","1326–1379":"1326–1379","1342–1374":"1342–1374","1273–Male":"1273–Décédé","1280–1312":"1280–1312","1326":"1326","1379":"1379","1312":"1312","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","Aft. 1312":"après 1312","1342":"1342","1374